	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Inequalities in supply chain hold back transmission of high prices to producers in Kenya</h1>

			
			<h4>
												03 April 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Kenyan coffee prices were up ‘an average of 16%’ above corresponding prices in 2010 at the first auction sales of 2011. For some consignments of premium ‘AA grade’ coffee, prices were up 40%. This reflected ‘the dearth of high quality beans for sale’, according to Nairobi Coffee Exchange official Daniel Mbithi. Kenyan production – at 40,000 tonnes – is down 5,000 tonnes from last year, and substantially below the 49-50,000 tonnes of predicted production as a result of poor weather. Price developments also reflect global price trends, with the price outlook described as ‘bright’ by Daniel Mbithi. In December 2010, international prices for arabica coffee varieties (Kenya’s main product) rose sharply to a 16-year high.</p><p>According to the International Coffee Organisation (ICO), ‘the current supply situation/demand structure has reinforced the continued firmness in prices throughout 2010’, while ‘current developments in market fundamentals suggest that prices will remain firm during 2011.’ These developments include:</p>
<ul>

<li>buoyant consumer demand; </li>

<li>disease outbreak scares in some countries; </li>

<li>adverse weather in some regions, ‘disrupting harvesting and transportation’. </li>

</ul>
<p>Nevertheless ICO projects an estimated 9.6% increase in production, including in the neighbouring East African producers of Ethiopia, Tanzania and Uganda.</p><p>Despite these favourable international market conditions, Kenya Co-operative Coffee Exporters Ltd (KCCE) has warned that ‘the existence of cartels in the local coffee supply chain has over the years denied farmers the benefits of the expected bonanza.’ KCCE managing director Lucy Murumba said that the ‘total control has contributed to price manipulation and as a result, small scale coffee farmers have had little reason to invest in higher quality production leading to a vicious cycle of declining earnings and lower yield per hectare.’ According to press reports, incidents of theft and illegal trading in coffee have also increased in response to rising prices.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>Business Daily </i>(Nairobi), ‘Coffee earnings outlook bright as supply shrinks’, 17 January 2011<br />

