<i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘Supply fears drive Kenya coffee to $20,000 a tonne’, 18 January 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/supply-fears-drive-kenya-coffee-to-000-a-tonne--2717.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/supply-fears-drive-kenya-coffee-to-000-a-t...</a><br />
<i>Agrimoney.com</i>, ‘ICO lifts coffee crop hopes despite Colombian woes’, 12 January 2011<br />
<a href="http://www.agrimoney.com/news/ico-lifts-coffee-crop-hopes-despite-colombian-woes--2696.html" target="_self">http://www.agrimoney.com/news/ico-lifts-coffee-crop-hopes-despite-colomb...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Increasingly producing quality-differentiated coffee is likely to provide the best insulation against extreme price volatility. Where aspects of the functioning of a given supply chain create obstacles to the progressive promotion of quality-differentiated production, there would appear to be a role for government-led, stakeholder-driven measures to strengthen the functioning of the supply chain. This would appear to be the case in the Kenyan coffee sector, where coffee farmers’ leaders allege price manipulation that has the effect of discouraging on-farm investment in ‘higher quality production’.</p><p>However, such action cannot be undertaken without a thorough analysis of the functioning of individual supply chains. It is against this background that the recent Tanzanian experience of reviewing the functioning of the cotton supply chain could be relevant (see <i>Agritrade </i>article, ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Regions/ACP/West-Africa" target="_blank">Improving the functioning of the supply chain seen as key to Tanzanian c...</a>’, March 2011). Identifying critical constraints and appropriate ways of improving the functioning of supply chains could go a long way towards laying solid foundations for greater on-farm investment in quality-differentiated coffee production.</p>
		</div>
		
